{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3e604321-96fc-490e-8baa-4baabb4142e3","content":"**`ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"`** — ✅ Yes, this is correct for .NET MAUI (including .NET 10). You need the iOS platform-specific namespace:\n\n```xml\n<ContentPage xmlns:ios=\"clr-namespace:Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;assembly=Microsoft.Maui.Controls\"\n             ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\">\n```\n\n**`IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` on a Grid** — ❌ This is **not** a built-in .NET MAUI property. That tutorial may be outdated or referencing a third-party library.\n\nFor a full-bleed background image, the typical approach is:\n\n1. **Don't** set `UseSafeArea` on the page (or set it to `False`).\n2. Use a `Grid` with an `Image` that fills edge-to-edge as the first child.\n3. Place your content in a second child layout and bind its `Padding` to `On<iOS>().SafeAreaInsets()` in code-behind, or just set `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` on an inner content layer.\n\n```xml\n<Grid>\n    <!-- Background fills entire screen including behind notch -->\n    <Image Source=\"bg.png\" Aspect=\"AspectFill\" />\n\n    <!-- Content respects safe area via manual padding -->\n    <StackLayout x:Name=\"Content\" ...>\n        ...\n    </StackLayout>\n</Grid>\n```\n\n```csharp\n// Code-behind\nusing Microsoft.Maui.Controls.PlatformConfiguration.iOSSpecific;\n\nvar insets = On<iOS>().SafeAreaInsets();\nContent.Padding = insets;\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cf0d6432-d921-4e2e-a236-6475bd6abe68","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about .NET MAUI safe area handling on iOS, specifically about two properties:\n\n1. `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` - a platform-specific property for ContentPage\n2. `IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` - on a Grid for background images\n\nLet me think about what I know about .NET MAUI safe area APIs:\n\nIn .NET MAUI, the iOS safe area handling has evolved. Let me recall:\n\n- In Xamarin.Forms, there was `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` as a platform-specific.\n\n\n- In .NET MAUI, this was carried forward but the API surface may have changed.\n\nActually, in .NET MAUI:\n- `Page.UseSafeArea` is an iOS platform-specific that can be set via `ios:Page.UseSafeArea=\"True\"` where `ios` is the iOS platform namespace.\n- For ignoring safe area on specific views, there's `ios:VisualElement.IgnoreSafeArea=\"True\"` or similar.\n\nLet me think more carefully about the exact APIs available in .NET MAUI for controlling safe area behavior on iOS.\n\nSetting up the XAML namespace...\n\nI'm realizing that `IgnoreSafeArea` isn't actually a standard property in .NET MAUI—the way to handle safe areas on iOS is through `Page.UseSafeArea`, which controls whether content respects the safe area boundaries. For background images that need to extend behind the safe area while keeping text and interactive elements inset, I'd need a different layout approach rather than relying on a non-existent property. `IgnoreSafeArea` isn't actually a built-in MAUI property—it might be from a third-party library or a misremembering from another framework. For the background image use case, I should skip `UseSafeArea` on the page entirely and instead let the background fill the full screen while manually applying safe area padding to the content inside.","outputTokens":1442},"id":"d7a106fa-3065-43be-93a6-dba4a60dc802","timestamp":"2026-04-08T00:56:48.860Z","parentId":"fa9dbd38-4320-4a96-acce-cd48bdf41601"}
